The efficient separation and recombination preventing electron-hole pairs, which are related to GQDs-based heterojunctions, has led to an increase in photocatalytic efficiency. On the other hand, the CB of the GQDs located above the conduction band (CB) of CaSiO3 nanoparticles, and giving an energy difference to transfer the electron in CB of the GQDs to the CB of CaSiO3 (Scheme 2
                           ) then electrons are trapped, and the enhanced photocatalytic response in the nanostructures could be explained based on doping of GQDs with CaSiO3 nanoparticles. Synthesis of photocatalyst materials based on doping with GQDs is a promising approach to increase the potential of pollutant purification. Table 3
                            reviews the photocatalytic activity of different nanostructures combing with GQDs. As revealed in this table, CaSiO3/GQDs nanocomposites can compete with other nanocomposites and have efficient activity in the visible area.
